{"id":"2203.12846","submitter":"Gabor Fodor","authors":"G\\'abor Fodor, Sebastian Fodor, Mikl\\'os Telek","title":"On the Achievable SINR in MU-MIMO Systems Operating in Time-Varying\n  Rayleigh Fading","comments":"15 pages, 9 figures, 4 tables","journal-ref":"IEEE Trans. on Communications (under the incorrect title \"MU-MIMO\n  Receiver Design and Performance Analysis in Time-Varying Rayleigh Fading\"),\n  Vol. 70, Issue 2, pp. 1214-1228, Feb. 2022.\n  https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/9606935","doi":"10.1109/TCOMM.2021.3126760.","report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Minimizing the symbol error in the uplink of multi-user multiple input\nmultiple output systems is important, because the symbol error affects the\nachieved signal-to-interference-plus-noise ratio (SINR) and thereby the\nspectral efficiency of the system. Despite the vast literature available on\nminimum mean squared error (MMSE) receivers, previously proposed receivers for\nblock fading channels do not minimize the symbol error in time-varying Rayleigh\nfading channels. Specifically, we show that the true MMSE receiver structure\ndoes not only depend on the statistics of the CSI error, but also on the\nautocorrelation coefficient of the time-variant channel. It turns out that\ncalculating the average SINR when using the proposed receiver is highly\nnon-trivial. In this paper, we employ a random matrix theoretical approach,\nwhich allows us to derive a quasi-closed form for the average SINR, which\nallows to obtain analytical exact results that give valuable insights into how\nthe SINR depends on the number of antennas, employed pilot and data power and\nthe covariance of the time-varying channel. We benchmark the performance of the\nproposed receiver against recently proposed receivers and find that the\nproposed MMSE receiver achieves higher SINR than the previously proposed ones,\nand this benefit increases with increasing autoregressive coefficient.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 24 Mar 2022 04:57:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-25"}
